  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Understanding customer financial activities\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Submitting suspicious activity reports (SARs)\n- Filing currency transaction reports (CTRs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n\n3. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer identification information\n- Retaining records for specified periods\n\n4. Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal AML policies\n- Training employees\n- Implementing monitoring systems\n\n5. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers/transactions\n- Conducting ongoing risk evaluations\n- Implementing enhanced monitoring\n\n6. Legal Regulations\n- Compliance with Bank Secrecy Act\n- Following Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Adhering to local and international AML regulations\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, including substantial fines and potential criminal charges.\n\nFinancial institutions must proactively prevent money laundering and report potential illicit financial activities.",
